{"title_page": "Tsubasa Fukuchi", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image = <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people.  See [[WP:NONFREE]].  -->\n| image_size = 150px |\n| name=Tsubasa Fukuchi\n| caption     = \n| birth_name=%7C birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|2|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Nikk\u014d, Tochigi]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| residence   = \n| known_for   = ''[[The Law of Ueki]]''\n| occupation  = [[mangaka|Manga artist]]\n| website     = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Tsubasa Fukuchi'''|\u798f\u5730\u7ffc|Fukuchi Tsubasa|born February 7, 1980}} is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] manga artist, best known for being the creator of ''[[The Law of Ueki]]'' and its sequel, ''[[The Law of Ueki Plus]]''. Fukuchi's most recent manga, ''Psyche Mata Shite mo'', debuted in 2014 in ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Law of Ueki's Fukuchi Starts Psyche Mata Shite mo Manga |url=/news/2014-07-09/law-of-ueki-fukuchi-starts-psyche-mata-shite-mo-manga/.76480 |website=Anime News Network |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n''The Law of Ueki'' was adapted into a 51\u2013episode anime series.<ref>{{cite web|url=/anime/ueki/|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247|publisher=[[TV Tokyo]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nManga artists Ato Sakurai (author of ''[[Artist Acro]]'') and Ry\u014d Azuchi (author of ''[[Softenni]]'') were once his assistants.\n\n==Early life==\nTsubasa Fukuchi was born in [[Tochigi Prefecture]], north of Tokyo. He won his first prize in 1998, at Manga College contest with his work ''K\u014dderi'' at the age of 18. Fukuchi began his professional career in 2001 with ''[[The Law of Ueki]]''.\n\n==Works==\n*{{nihongo|''[[The Law of Ueki]]''|\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247|''Ueki no H\u014dsoku''}} (2001\u20132005, serialized in ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday]]'', [[Shogakukan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=/comics/detail/_isbn_4091263410|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247 1|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=/comics/detail/_isbn_4091270360|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247 16|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*{{nihongo|''[[The Law of Ueki Plus]]''|\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247\u30d7\u30e9\u30b9|''Ueki no H\u014dsoku Purasu''}} (2005\u20132007, serialized in ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday'', Shogakukan)<ref>{{cite web|url=/comics/detail/_isbn_4091270379|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247\u30d7\u30e9\u30b9 1|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=/comics/detail/_isbn_9784091211897|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247\u30d7\u30e9\u30b9 5|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*{{nihongo||\u30bf\u30c3\u30b3\u30af!!!|''Takkoku!!!''}} (2009\u20132011, serialized in ''[[Sh\u014dnen Sunday Super]]'', Shogakukan)<ref>{{cite web|url=/comics/detail/_isbn_9784091217561|script-title=ja:\u30bf\u30c3\u30b3\u30af!!! 1|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=/comics/detail/_isbn_9784091223173|script-title=ja:\u30bf\u30c3\u30b3\u30af!!! 3|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*''[[Anagle Mole]]'' (2011\u20132014, serialized in ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday'', Shogakukan)\n*{{nihongo|''[[Psyche Matashitemo]]'' |\u30b5\u30a4\u30b1\u307e\u305f\u3057\u3066\u3082|''Saike Mata Shitemo''}} (2014\u20132018, serialized in ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday'', Shogakukan)\n<!-- *{{nihongo|||}} -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ann|people|22897}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fukuchi, Tsubasa}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Manga artists]]\n[[Category:Manga artists from Tochigi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:White supremacists]]\n[[Category:Hentai creators]]\n\n{{manga-artist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image = <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people.  See [[WP:NONFREE]].  -->\n| image_size = 150px |\n| name        = Tsubasa Fukuchi\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|2|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Nikk\u014d, Tochigi]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| residence   = \n| known_for   = ''[[The Law of Ueki]]''\n| occupation  = [[mangaka|Manga artist]]\n| website     = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Tsubasa Fukuchi'''|\u798f\u5730\u7ffc|Fukuchi Tsubasa|born February 7, 1980}} is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] manga artist, best known for being the creator of ''[[The Law of Ueki]]'' and its sequel, ''[[The Law of Ueki Plus]]''. Fukuchi's most recent manga, ''Psyche Mata Shite mo'', debuted in 2014 in ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Law of Ueki's Fukuchi Starts Psyche Mata Shite mo Manga |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-07-09/law-of-ueki-fukuchi-starts-psyche-mata-shite-mo-manga/.76480 |website=Anime News Network |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n''The Law of Ueki'' was adapted into a 51\u2013episode anime series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/anime/ueki/|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247|publisher=[[TV Tokyo]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nManga artists Ato Sakurai (author of ''[[Artist Acro]]'') and Ry\u014d Azuchi (author of ''[[Softenni]]'') were once his assistants.\n\n==Early life==\nTsubasa Fukuchi was born in [[Tochigi Prefecture]], north of Tokyo. He won his first prize in 1998, at Manga College contest with his work ''K\u014dderi'' at the age of 18. Fukuchi began his professional career in 2001 with ''[[The Law of Ueki]]''.\n\n==Works==\n*{{nihongo|''[[The Law of Ueki]]''|\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247|''Ueki no H\u014dsoku''}} (2001\u20132005, serialized in ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday]]'', [[Shogakukan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogakukan.co.jp/comics/detail/_isbn_4091263410|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247 1|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogakukan.co.jp/comics/detail/_isbn_4091270360|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247 16|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*{{nihongo|''[[The Law of Ueki Plus]]''|\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247\u30d7\u30e9\u30b9|''Ueki no H\u014dsoku Purasu''}} (2005\u20132007, serialized in ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday'', Shogakukan)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogakukan.co.jp/comics/detail/_isbn_4091270379|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247\u30d7\u30e9\u30b9 1|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogakukan.co.jp/comics/detail/_isbn_9784091211897|script-title=ja:\u3046\u3048\u304d\u306e\u6cd5\u5247\u30d7\u30e9\u30b9 5|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*{{nihongo||\u30bf\u30c3\u30b3\u30af!!!|''Takkoku!!!''}} (2009\u20132011, serialized in ''[[Sh\u014dnen Sunday Super]]'', Shogakukan)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogakukan.co.jp/comics/detail/_isbn_9784091217561|script-title=ja:\u30bf\u30c3\u30b3\u30af!!! 1|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogakukan.co.jp/comics/detail/_isbn_9784091223173|script-title=ja:\u30bf\u30c3\u30b3\u30af!!! 3|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*''[[Anagle Mole]]'' (2011\u20132014, serialized in ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday'', Shogakukan)\n*{{nihongo|''[[Psyche Matashitemo]]'' |\u30b5\u30a4\u30b1\u307e\u305f\u3057\u3066\u3082|''Saike Mata Shitemo''}} (2014\u20132018, serialized in ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday'', Shogakukan)\n<!-- *{{nihongo|||}} -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ann|people|22897}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fukuchi, Tsubasa}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Manga artists]]\n[[Category:Manga artists from Tochigi Prefecture]]\n\n\n{{manga-artist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "216.222.194.236", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Justin Knapp > Weekly Shonen Sunday)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsubasa_Fukuchi"}
{"title_page": "Madhouse (ride)", "text_new": "{{Infobox attraction model\n| name                   = Madhouse\n| status                 = In production\n| first_produced         = 1996\n| No. of installations   = 16\n| manufacturer           = Vekoma\n| capacity               = 685/1335\n| custom_label_1         = Seat capacity\n| custom_value_1         = 40/78\n| custom_label_2         = Gondola rotation\n| custom_value_2         = 15/30 degrees\n| custom_label_3         = Drum rotation\n| custom_value_3         = 360 degrees\n}}\n{{Infobox attraction model\n| name                   = Mystery Swing\n| status                 = In production\n| first_produced         = 2000\n| No. of installations   = 4\n| manufacturer           = Mack Rides\n| custom_label_1         = Seat capacity\n| custom_value_1         = 52\n}}\nA '''Madhouse''' is a flat ride usually manufactured by [[Vekoma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coasterforce.com/Vekoma |title=Vekoma |website=coasterforce.com |accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref><ref name=\"vekoma\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vekoma.com/mad-house |title=Mad House {{!}} Vekoma Rides Manufacturing BV |website=vekoma.com |accessdate=2019-06-12}}</ref> A similar attraction under the name '''Mystery Swing''' is created by [[Mack Rides]].<ref>{{cite web|title=''Mystery Swing'' by Mack Rides|url=https://mack-rides.com/products/dark-rides/mystery-swing/|website=mack-rides.com|accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref> The ride is designed to be an [[optical illusion|optical]] and physical [[illusion]], consisting of several rows of seats attached to a swaying gondola within a rotating drum. The ride creates the impression that the rider is turning upside down, whereas it is actually the room that is moving around them.\n\nThe ride is a modern implementation of a [[haunted swing]] illusion.\n\n==Ride experience==\nMadhouses are often extensively themed during the ride sequence, and usually in the [[Queue area|queue line]]. Several Madhouses feature pre-shows explaining a story behind the ride. Once in the ride, lapbars are lowered onto the riders, before they gradually experience an odd sense of [[:wikt:movement|movement]]. This is achieved through two mechanisms - the separate floor can move in a controlled swing from side-to-side by up to 15/30 degrees in each direction, but the surroundings of the room can rotate through a full 360 degrees. The [[Rotation|pivot]] mechanism for the floor is hidden by two large objects at the end of the room, which are themed to match the ride.\n\nAt this point, both the floor and the room are slowly moving in unison. As the ride continues, the floor starts a separate movement from the rotating drum which gradually gives the impression that the room is rotating backwards and forwards further each time. Vekoma offers theme parks the option of programming their own sequence of how the room and floor move. In many Madhouses, the [[lighting]] subtly changes from moment to moment to add to the [[disorientation]]. Eventually, the drum mechanism turns through a full rotation and, by careful [[synchronisation]] with the sensation of the swinging floor mechanism, the riders are fooled into feeling as if they themselves are being repeatedly turned upside down.<ref name=\"vekoma\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=''Revolving House'' by Mack Rides|url=http://www.mack-rides.com/en/products/dark-rides/revolving-house/dr-rh-info/dr-rh-info.html|website=mack-rides.com|accessdate=2014-11-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017135818/http://www.mack-rides.com/en/products/dark-rides/revolving-house/dr-rh-info/index.html |archivedate=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Video of the mechanism|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SppOrEx8DvA|website=youtube.com|accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref>\n\n== List of Madhouses ==\n[[File:Villa Volta Efteling 2018.jpg|thumb|Interior of [[Villa Volta]], the first modern madhouse.]]\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n! Name !! Park !! Country !! Opened 